## 2. System Architecture

### 2.1 Architecture Overview

The fix targets the data flow path within kiro-rs where tool\_use\_id is transformed during response conversion. The architecture remains unchanged — only the internal behavior of the converter module is corrected.

Architecture Diagram [*Edit in draw.io*](diagrams/architecture.drawio)

**Key Invariant (Post-Fix):**

Kiro Q API response.content[i].id == SSE stream content\_block.id == history.messages[n].content[i].id

All three locations MUST hold the exact same string value for any given tool invocation.

### 2.2 Component Diagram

The converter module consists of four logical components that participate in the tool\_use\_id flow:

Component Diagram [*Edit in draw.io*](diagrams/component.drawio)

| Component | Responsibility | Change Required |
| --- | --- | --- |
| converter.rs | Transforms Kiro Q response → SSE format | **YES** — remove ID generation, passthrough original |
| handlers.rs | HTTP handler, SSE streaming, history storage | **YES** — ensure stored ID matches streamed ID |
| types.rs | Data structures (ContentBlock, ToolUseBlock) | No — structs already support String id field |
| ConversationHistory | In-memory message store with lookup | **YES** — add find\_tool\_use() and diagnostic methods |

### 2.3 Communication Patterns

| From | To | Protocol | Pattern | Description |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| VS Code Extension | kiro-rs | HTTP POST | Sync (Request-Response) | chatWithTools request |
| kiro-rs | VS Code Extension | SSE | Async (Server-push) | Streaming response with tool\_use blocks |
| kiro-rs | Kiro Q API | HTTP POST | Sync (Request-Response) | Forwarded chat request |
| Kiro Q API | kiro-rs | HTTP Response | Sync | JSON response with tool\_use content blocks |
| VS Code Extension | kiro-rs | HTTP POST | Sync | Continuation request with toolResult |

## 3. API Design

**Prerequisite:** Functional API contracts are defined in FSD §3.1.6. This section specifies the technical implementation details.

### 3.1 API Overview

| # | Endpoint | Method | Description | Source |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| 1 | /chat/completions | POST | Chat with tools (initial + continuation) | UC-1, UC-2 |

### 3.2 API: POST /chat/completions

**Implements:** UC-1 (ReAct Tool Loop), UC-2 (Diagnostic Error), BR-1 through BR-9

| Attribute | Value |
| --- | --- |
| Method | POST |
| Path | /chat/completions |
| Auth | Internal (extension ↔ kiro-rs trust boundary) |
| Rate Limit | N/A (local service) |
| Response Type | SSE (text/event-stream) |

**Request Body (Initial Request):**

{
 "messages": [
 { "role": "user", "content": "Read file X and analyze it" }
 ],
 "tools": [
 { "name": "readFile", "description": "...", "input\_schema": {...} }
 ]
}

**Request Body (Continuation Request):**

{
 "messages": [...],
 "toolResult": {
 "toolUseId": "tooluse\_490CxYz123",
 "content": "file contents here...",
 "isError": false
 }
}

**Response — SSE Stream (tool\_use):**

event: content\_block\_start
data: {"content\_block": {"type": "tool\_use", "id": "tooluse\_490CxYz123", "name": "readFile"}}

event: content\_block\_delta
data: {"delta": {"type": "input\_json\_delta", "partial\_json": "{\"path\": \"/src/main.rs\"}"}}

event: content\_block\_stop
data: {}

event: message\_stop
data: {}

**Critical:** The id field in content\_block\_start MUST be the verbatim value from Kiro Q API response (BR-1).

**Error Responses:**

| Status | Code | Message | Trigger Condition |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| 400 | TOOL\_USE\_ID\_NOT\_FOUND | “tool\_use\_id ‘{id}’ not found in conversation history. Available IDs: […]” | Continuation with unmatched toolUseId (BR-6, BR-8) |
| 400 | MALFORMED\_API\_RESPONSE | “Received malformed tool\_use response from API (missing id field)” | Kiro Q returns tool\_use without id |
| 400 | EMPTY\_TOOL\_USE\_ID | “Invalid tool\_use\_id: value cannot be empty” | Empty string ID (BR-3) |
| 500 | HISTORY\_STORAGE\_FAILURE | “Internal error during tool processing” | Failed to store in history |

## 4. Data Model Design

**Prerequisite:** Logical entities defined in FSD §4. This section specifies in-memory Rust struct design.

### 4.1 Data Structures (No Database — In-Memory Only)

This feature has no persistent database. All data lives in-memory during a conversation session.

#### Struct: ConversationMessage

#[derive(Debug, Clone, Serialize, Deserialize)]
pub struct ConversationMessage {
 pub role: MessageRole,
 pub content: Vec<ContentBlock>,
 pub turn\_number: u32,
}

#[derive(Debug, Clone, Serialize, Deserialize)]
pub enum MessageRole {
 User,
 Assistant,
 ToolResult,
}

#### Struct: ContentBlock

#[derive(Debug, Clone, Serialize, Deserialize)]
#[serde(tag = "type")]
pub enum ContentBlock {
 #[serde(rename = "text")]
 Text { text: String },

 #[serde(rename = "tool\_use")]
 ToolUse {
 id: String, // BR-1: Preserved verbatim from API
 name: String,
 input: serde\_json::Value,
 },

 #[serde(rename = "tool\_result")]
 ToolResult {
 tool\_use\_id: String, // BR-2: Must match stored tool\_use.id
 content: String,
 is\_error: bool,
 },
}

#### Struct: ConversationHistory

pub struct ConversationHistory {
 messages: Vec<ConversationMessage>,
 current\_turn: u32,
}

impl ConversationHistory {
 /// Store assistant message. tool\_use\_id values within content blocks
 /// are preserved exactly as received from the API.
 pub fn push\_assistant\_message(&mut self, content: Vec<ContentBlock>) {
 self.current\_turn += 1;
 self.messages.push(ConversationMessage {
 role: MessageRole::Assistant,
 content,
 turn\_number: self.current\_turn,
 });
 }

 /// Find a tool\_use block by ID. Returns None if not found.
 /// Used during continuation matching (BR-2).
 pub fn find\_tool\_use(&self, tool\_use\_id: &str) -> Option<&ContentBlock> {
 self.messages.iter()
 .flat\_map(|msg| msg.content.iter())
 .find(|block| matches!(block, ContentBlock::ToolUse { id, .. } if id == tool\_use\_id))
 }

 /// Get all stored tool\_use\_ids for diagnostic logging (BR-7).
 pub fn get\_all\_tool\_use\_ids(&self) -> Vec<&str> {
 self.messages.iter()
 .flat\_map(|msg| msg.content.iter())
 .filter\_map(|block| match block {
 ContentBlock::ToolUse { id, .. } => Some(id.as\_str()),
 \_ => None,
 })
 .collect()
 }

 pub fn current\_turn\_number(&self) -> u32 {
 self.current\_turn
 }
}

### 4.2 Data Flow Invariant

┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ Kiro Q API Response SSE Stream │
│ content[i].id = "tooluse\_XYZ" content\_block.id = "tooluse\_XYZ" │
│ │ ▲ │
│ │ SAME VALUE │ │
│ ▼ │ │
│ ConversationHistory │ │
│ messages[n].content[i].id = "tooluse\_XYZ" ──┘ │
│ │ │
│ │ MATCHES │
│ ▼ │
│ Continuation Request │
│ toolResult.toolUseId = "tooluse\_XYZ" │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

## 5. Class / Module Design

### 5.1 Package Structure

kiro-rs/src/anthropic/
├── mod.rs # Module declaration
├── converter.rs # ← PRIMARY FIX: Response/request conversion
├── handlers.rs # ← SECONDARY FIX: HTTP handlers + history management
├── types.rs # Data structures (ContentBlock, etc.)
└── tests/
 ├── converter\_test.rs # Unit tests for converter
 ├── handlers\_test.rs # Integration tests for handler flow
 └── id\_passthrough\_test.rs # Specific regression tests for this fix

### 5.2 Key Changes in converter.rs

**Before (Broken):**

// BUG: This generates a NEW id instead of using the API's id
fn convert\_tool\_use\_block(api\_block: &ApiToolUseBlock) -> SseContentBlock {
 SseContentBlock::ToolUse {
 id: generate\_tool\_use\_id(), // ← ROOT CAUSE: new ID generated
 name: api\_block.name.clone(),
 input: api\_block.input.clone(),
 }
}

**After (Fixed):**

// FIX: Pass through the original id from Kiro Q API (BR-1)
fn convert\_tool\_use\_block(api\_block: &ApiToolUseBlock) -> Result<SseContentBlock, ConversionError> {
 // BR-3: Validate id is non-empty
 if api\_block.id.is\_empty() {
 return Err(ConversionError::EmptyToolUseId);
 }

 // BR-1: Use verbatim id — NO generation, NO transformation
 Ok(SseContentBlock::ToolUse {
 id: api\_block.id.clone(), // ← FIX: passthrough original
 name: api\_block.name.clone(),
 input: api\_block.input.clone(),
 })
}

### 5.3 Key Changes in handlers.rs

**Continuation Matching (BR-2, BR-6, BR-7, BR-8):**

async fn handle\_continuation(
 history: &ConversationHistory,
 tool\_result: &ToolResultRequest,
) -> Result<ApiRequest, HandlerError> {
 let tool\_use\_id = &tool\_result.tool\_use\_id;

 // BR-2: Match toolResult.toolUseId against history
 match history.find\_tool\_use(tool\_use\_id) {
 Some(\_) => {
 // Match found — construct valid API request
 tracing::trace!(
 tool\_use\_id = %tool\_use\_id,
 turn = history.current\_turn\_number(),
 "tool\_use\_id matched in history"
 );
 Ok(build\_continuation\_request(history, tool\_result))
 }
 None => {
 // BR-6, BR-7: Log diagnostic warning
 let stored\_ids = history.get\_all\_tool\_use\_ids();
 tracing::warn!(
 received\_id = %tool\_use\_id,
 stored\_ids = ?stored\_ids,
 turn = history.current\_turn\_number(),
 "tool\_use\_id not found in conversation history"
 );

 // BR-8: Return descriptive error (not generic 400)
 Err(HandlerError::ToolUseIdNotFound {
 received\_id: tool\_use\_id.clone(),
 available\_ids: stored\_ids.iter().map(|s| s.to\_string()).collect(),
 turn\_number: history.current\_turn\_number(),
 })
 }
 }
}

### 5.4 Error Handling

| Error Type | HTTP Status | Error Code | When Thrown | Implements |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| ConversionError::EmptyToolUseId | 400 | EMPTY\_TOOL\_USE\_ID | API returns empty id | BR-3 |
| ConversionError::MissingIdField | 400 | MALFORMED\_API\_RESPONSE | API returns tool\_use without id | EF-2 |
| HandlerError::ToolUseIdNotFound | 400 | TOOL\_USE\_ID\_NOT\_FOUND | Continuation ID not in history | BR-6, BR-8 |
| HandlerError::HistoryStorageFailure | 500 | HISTORY\_STORAGE\_FAILURE | Mutex/lock failure | EF-3 |

### 5.5 Design Patterns

| Pattern | Where Used | Rationale |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Passthrough (no transformation) | converter.rs ID handling | BR-1: IDs must not be modified |
| Result/Error propagation | All conversion functions | Rust idiomatic error handling |
| Structured logging | handler boundaries | BR-7: Diagnostic trace at each point |
| Interior mutability (Arc) | ConversationHistory | Thread-safe async access |

## 6. Integration Design

**Prerequisite:** Integration requirements defined in FSD §5.

### 6.1 External System: Kiro Q API

| Attribute | Value |
| --- | --- |
| Protocol | HTTPS |
| Endpoint | Configured via environment/config |
| Authentication | Service credentials (existing) |
| Timeout | Existing configuration (no change) |
| Retry Policy | Existing configuration (no change) |
| Circuit Breaker | Not applicable for this fix |

**Data Mapping (Response → Internal):**

| Kiro Q Field | Internal Field | Transformation |
| --- | --- | --- |
| response.content[i].id | ContentBlock::ToolUse.id | **NONE** (verbatim copy) |
| response.content[i].name | ContentBlock::ToolUse.name | Clone |
| response.content[i].input | ContentBlock::ToolUse.input | Clone (serde\_json::Value) |

### 6.2 External System: VS Code Extension

| Attribute | Value |
| --- | --- |
| Protocol | HTTP + SSE |
| Direction | Bidirectional |
| Timeout | Client-managed |

**Data Mapping (Internal → SSE Stream):**

| Internal Field | SSE Field | Transformation |
| --- | --- | --- |
| ContentBlock::ToolUse.id | content\_block.id | **NONE** (verbatim) |
| ContentBlock::ToolUse.name | content\_block.name | Direct |
| ContentBlock::ToolUse.input | delta.partial\_json | Serialized, chunked |

**Data Mapping (Continuation → Internal):**

| Extension Field | Internal Field | Transformation |
| --- | --- | --- |
| toolResult.toolUseId | tool\_use\_id lookup key | **NONE** (used as-is for matching) |
| toolResult.content | ContentBlock::ToolResult.content | Direct |
| toolResult.isError | ContentBlock::ToolResult.is\_error | Direct |

## 7. Security Design

**Prerequisite:** Security requirements defined in FSD §7.

### 7.1 Authentication

No changes to authentication model. kiro-rs operates as a local service trusted by the VS Code extension. Service-to-Kiro Q API authentication uses existing credentials.

### 7.2 Data Protection

| Data Type | Classification | Protection |
| --- | --- | --- |
| tool\_use\_id | Internal identifier | No PII, no encryption needed |
| Tool input/output | User workspace data | In-transit only (local HTTP) |
| Conversation history | Ephemeral | In-memory, cleared on session end |

### 7.3 Input Validation

| Field | Validation | Implements |
| --- | --- | --- |
| tool\_use\_id (from API) | Non-empty string | BR-3 |
| tool\_use\_id (from extension) | Non-empty, exists in history | BR-2, BR-6 |
| tool\_use\_id format | Pattern: tooluse\_[A-Za-z0-9]+ | BR-3 (advisory, not enforced) |

### 7.4 Logging Security

* tool\_use\_id values logged at TRACE level (no sensitive data)
* Tool input/output NOT logged (may contain user code)
* Conversation content NOT logged beyond structure metadata

## 8. Performance & Scalability

**Prerequisite:** NFR targets defined in FSD §8.

### 8.1 Performance Impact Analysis

| Operation | Before Fix | After Fix | Difference |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Response conversion | ~0.1ms (includes ID generation) | ~0.05ms (clone only) | -50% (faster) |
| History storage | ~0.01ms | ~0.01ms | No change |
| Continuation matching | ~0.1ms (broken) | ~0.1ms (working) | Functional fix, no perf change |

The fix actually **improves** performance by removing the unnecessary ID generation step.

### 8.2 Concurrency

| Resource | Strategy | Implementation |
| --- | --- | --- |
| ConversationHistory | Arc<Mutex> | Existing pattern — no change needed |
| Multiple tool\_use blocks in one response | Sequential processing within single lock | BR-5: Each block’s ID preserved independently |

### 8.3 Performance Targets

| Operation | Target | Measurement |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Full ReAct loop (chat → tool → continue) | < 100ms overhead (excluding API latency) | tokio::time instrumentation |
| ID passthrough conversion | < 1ms | No measurable difference from String::clone() |
| History lookup | O(n) where n = total tool calls in session | Acceptable for typical sessions (< 100 tool calls) |

## 9. Monitoring & Observability

### 9.1 Logging

| Log Event | Level | Fields | Implements |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| tool\_use\_id received from API | TRACE | tool\_use\_id, tool\_name, turn | BR-7 |
| tool\_use\_id emitted in SSE stream | TRACE | tool\_use\_id, tool\_name | BR-7 |
| tool\_use\_id stored in history | TRACE | tool\_use\_id, turn | BR-7 |
| Continuation match SUCCESS | TRACE | tool\_use\_id, turn | BR-7 |
| Continuation match FAILURE | WARN | received\_id, stored\_ids, turn | BR-6, BR-7 |
| Empty/missing tool\_use\_id from API | ERROR | response\_body\_fragment | BR-3 |

### 9.2 Metrics (Existing Framework)

| Metric | Type | Description | Alert Threshold |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| tool\_continuation\_success | Counter | Successful ID matches | N/A |
| tool\_continuation\_mismatch | Counter | Failed ID matches (post-fix: should be 0) | > 0 in 5 min window |
| tool\_use\_id\_empty | Counter | API returned empty/missing ID | > 0 |

### 9.3 Health Checks

No new health check endpoints needed. The existing health check remains unchanged.

## 10. Deployment Considerations

### 10.1 Deployment Strategy

| Aspect | Value |
| --- | --- |
| Deployment type | Binary replacement (Rust compiled binary) |
| Rollback | Replace binary with previous version |
| Feature flag | Not needed — this is a pure bug fix |
| Migration | None (no database, no persistent state) |

### 10.2 Rollback Strategy

1. If the fix introduces regressions, revert to the previous kiro-rs binary
2. No data migration needed — conversation history is ephemeral
3. The extension requires zero changes — it already sends the correct toolUseId

### 10.3 Testing Before Deploy

| Test | Command | Expected |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Unit tests | cargo test --package kiro-rs | All pass |
| Integration test | Manual: trigger tool-calling conversation | ReAct loop completes, no 400 errors |
| Regression test | Run existing test suite | No failures |

